Ballpark Factor Analysis: Comparing Players

Research Question

How do ballpark factors influence the hitting performance of two MLB players? This project investigates the home and away performance of Kyle Seager and Nolan Arenado, exploring how environmental and park dimensions impact key hitting metrics such as OPS, wOBA, and Hard-Hit Percentage.

Narrative Text

Reason why I want to investigate this topic: Ballpark factors are a critical, yet often underappreciated aspect of baseball analytics. Differences in dimensions, altitude, and other environmental conditions can significantly influence player performance. I chose to analyze Kyle Seager and Nolan Arenado because they play in ballparks with contrasting reputations: Seager at Globe Life Field and Arenado at Busch Stadium (formerly Coors Field). This comparison provides an intriguing case study to understand how hitters adapt to their environments.

One significant technical challenge: A major challenge I faced during this project was cleaning and organizing disparate data sources. The player performance data was spread across multiple CSV files, and some datasets lacked critical variables like OPS and Hard-Hit Percentage. I overcame this by carefully merging and transforming the data in R, ensuring consistency and accuracy for the analysis.

Data Source

Primary Data Source: MLB Player Statistics (aggregated from Baseball Savant and team sites)

Who collected it: Major League Baseball (MLB) and third-party data providers

When and why: Originally collected to track player and team performance metrics during games

Case: Each case represents an individual player’s performance in a single game (home or away)

Variables used:
- player_name: Name of the player
- game_date: Date of the game
- home_team: Team playing at home
- away_team: Opposing team
- home_away: Indicator for home or away game
- hrs: Home runs hit
- hits: Total hits
- ba: Batting average
- obp: On-base percentage
- slg: Slugging percentage
- iso: Isolated power
- xwoba: Expected weighted on-base average
- xba: Expected batting average
- xobp: Expected on-base percentage
- xslg: Expected slugging percentage
- babip: Batting average on balls in play
- bb: Walk rate

# Add player and location columns to each dataset
seager_home <- seager_home %>%
  mutate(player = "Seager", location = "Home")
seager_away <- seager_away %>%
  mutate(player = "Seager", location = "Away")
arenado_home <- arenado_home %>%
  mutate(player = "Arenado", location = "Home")
arenado_away <- arenado_away %>%
  mutate(player = "Arenado", location = "Away")

# Combine all datasets into one
combined_data <- bind_rows(seager_home, seager_away, arenado_home, arenado_away)

This code processes and combines baseball performance data for Kyle Seager and Nolan Arenado, comparing their home and away game performances. It first adds two columns—player (Seager or Arenado) and location (Home or Away)—to each dataset. Then, it merges all four datasets (Seager’s and Arenado’s home and away data) into one unified dataset using bind_rows(). The resulting combined data is ready for further analysis or visualization.

# Summarise key metrics
summary_data <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(player, location) %>%
  summarise(
    hrs = sum(hrs, na.rm = TRUE),
    hits = sum(hits, na.rm = TRUE),
    ba = mean(ba, na.rm = TRUE),
    obp = mean(obp, na.rm = TRUE),
    slg = mean(slg, na.rm = TRUE),
    xwoba = mean(xwoba, na.rm = TRUE),
    iso = mean(iso, na.rm = TRUE),
    babip = mean(babip, na.rm = TRUE),
    bb = sum(bb, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'player'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

This code summarizes key performance metrics for Kyle Seager and Nolan Arenado, grouped by player and location (home or away). It calculates the total home runs and walks, along with the average values for batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, expected wOBA, isolated power, and batting average on balls in play. Missing values are excluded using na.rm = TRUE.

# Example: Adding ballpark factors manually
ballpark_factors <- data.frame(
  location = c("Home", "Away"),
  park_factor = c(1.14, 0.94) # Adjust based on your actual data
)

# Join ballpark factors with summarised data
summary_data <- summary_data %>%
  left_join(ballpark_factors, by = "location")

This code adds ballpark factors to the summarized performance data by joining a manually created dataset (ballpark_factors) with the existing summary_data. The ballpark factors dataset includes location-specific adjustments (Home or Away), with park factors applied to each location. The left_join() function is used to merge these factors with the summary data based on the location column.

# Create a bar plot comparing Batting Average for Seager and Arenado, with ballpark factors displayed for Home location
ggplot(summary_data, aes(x = location, y = ba, fill = player)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") + # Bar plot with side-by-side comparison
  # Add park factors only for Home, specific to each player
  geom_text(
    aes(label = ifelse(location == "Home", paste(player, "PF:", park_factor), "")),
    position = position_dodge(width = 0.9), 
    vjust = -0.5, 
    size = 3 # Adding text labels for park factors
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Batting Average Comparison (Home vs Away) with Ballpark Factors",
    x = "Location",
    y = "Batting Percentage"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() # Clean, minimal theme

By comparing home and away batting averages, Arenado’s home batting average is significantly better than Seager’s, largely due to the favorable park factor of Coors Field. However, their away batting averages are nearly identical. This suggests that Coors Field positively impacts Arenado’s batting stats. In contrast, Seager performs better on the road, with a higher batting average in away games compared to his home games.

# Reshape the summary_data into long format

This code reshapes the summary_data dataset from wide to long format using the pivot_longer() function. It consolidates multiple performance metrics (hrs, hits, xwoba, iso, babip, bb) into two columns: metric (indicating the metric name) and value (containing the corresponding values). This transformation is useful for comparisons, visualizations, or further analysis.

ggplot(long_summary_data, aes(x = location, y = value, fill = player)) +

# Pivot longer and rename metrics
long_summary_data2 <- summary_data2 %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("avg_ba", "avg_obp", "avg_slg", "total_hits", "total_hrs"), 
               names_to = "metric", 
               values_to = "value") %>%
  mutate(
    metric = recode(
      metric,
      "avg_ba" = "BA",
      "avg_obp" = "OBP",
      "avg_slg" = "SLG",
      "total_hits" = "Total Hits",
      "total_hrs" = "Total Home Runs"
    )
  )

This code reshapes the summary_data2 dataset into a longer format using pivot_longer(), converting multiple performance metrics (batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, total hits, and total home runs) into key-value pairs. It also renames the metrics for clarity, changing column names such as “avg_ba” to “BA” and “total_hits” to “Total Hits.” This transformation makes the data more suitable for visualizations or further analysis.

ggplot(long_summary_data2, aes(x = location, y = value, fill = pitch_type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ metric + player, scales = "free_y") +  # Facet by metric and player
  labs(
    title = "Performance Comparison by Metric, Pitch Type, and Player (Home vs Away)",
    x = "Location",
    y = "Value"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "orange"))  # Custom color palette

This visualization compares Nolan Arenado’s and Kyle Seager’s hitting metrics (BA, OBP, SLG, Total Hits, and Total Home Runs) by location (home vs. away) and pitch type (Fastball vs. Other). Each player’s metrics are displayed in separate facets for clear comparison. The use of independent y-axes and distinct color coding—light blue for Fastball and orange for Other—effectively highlights the impact of pitch types on performance.

Key Observations Arenado’s Home Performance: 1. Fastball Dominance: Arenado performs exceptionally well on fastballs at home, with notable strengths in Total Hits and Total Home Runs. 2. Consistency on Away Games: His performance on both fastballs and other pitch types remains consistent only in away games, indicating that location has little impact on his success with these pitches outside of Coors Field. 3. Ballpark Effect: Coors Field’s hitter-friendly environment likely enhances Arenado’s performance, especially against fastballs.

Seager’s Away Performance: Away Game Advantage: Seager’s away stats outperform his home stats, particularly in Total Hits and Total Home Runs. This suggests that T-Mobile Park, Seager’s home park, has a pitcher-friendly environment that suppresses his performance, while he thrives in more neutral or hitter-friendly ballparks.

Approach to Pitch Types: 1. Arenado vs. Seager on Non-Fastballs: Arenado shows superior performance against non-fastball pitches both at home and away. suggesting he handles a variety of pitch types more effectively than Seager. 2. Seager’s Fastball Performance: Seager performs similarly to Arenado on fastballs but struggles more against other pitches, indicating less versatility in adapting to pitch variations.
